commits.message:
Login validated using formik

Login validated using formik, classes for input match the bootstrap style.

Logic for it to hit server is not included though. It does use a function called onSubmitUserLogin that can be used to hit the server then retrieved the necessary information.

As, to how it picks up and sends that information would  either have to use a cookie to store current session as being validated then allow the page to be viewied or to always have the pages be allowed to be viewable. And thus everytime a person goes to the page it will simply do a get request from the server for the information.

The user would need a unique id though. Using just the family name, firstname, and lastname will probably not be good when retrieving data.

Visuals overhaul

-Registration inputs updated for responsiveness
-alignment fixed for text
-validation fixed for number inputs on registration
-Star '*' added to indicate required input boxes
-Input added for user and password
-broken version of successful message and error message(will fix in next update).
-Summary screen updated for better visual feel
-Registration screens updated for a more logical grouping of inputs.

comment.body:
Okay. The branch was pushed to the github account.

I made the switch that controls the slides too complicated than necessary the first time around. Instead I re-used the switch as a function under the CreateUserPage. This will thus allow any stepscreen to have access to its old data during the previous button hit. This is accomplished by keeping the state within CreateUserPage and passing that state down to whatever the current slide is as the props(props.currentForm). 

One of the Yup(for first screen) was turned off for address line 2 due to it being optional(might need to get rid of that).

commits.message:
Persistence State + Splash Page Re-design

If you look at react dev tools, the state is actually being passed into the container component CreateUserPage. However, the form data is not persisting when using the previous button. This was fixed by transforming the switchcard from a component to a function that still returns JSX but inside of the CreateUserCard for now.

The props currentForm is what calls the form data being passed into whichever step the page is on for the current page. I'm too tired to explain more but it works now.

-also added the object merge for all the form data
-also added the ability to hit the post request to server but has to be hooked up to the server's data.
